Alright, let's fix #1540 once and for all. This adds support for rest elements in computed properties. It does so in a way that avoids the props.props.props.props thing we discovered ‚Äî in a case like this...
computed: {
  foo: ({ x, ...y }) => y
}
...foo will be excluded from the object passed in. This might seem slightly magical, but I think it matches people's intuitions of how this should work.

When no expression is used in a class directive the class name will be used to evaluate whether the class should be added/removed.
E.g. the following will add the class "active" when you call component.set({ active });.
<div class:active></div>
Also, classes added this way are encapsulated in the stylesheet.
Old
<div class="{active ? 'active' : ''}"></div>
<style>
.active {
  /* Will be removed from the stylesheet since the compiler can't know it is used */
}
</style>
New
<div class:active="active"></div>
<style>
.active {
  /* Will be kept and encapsulate styles */
}
</style>
